  "text": "We prove now that an MR distribution has an exponential tail day, i.e., it belongs to the class of sub-exponential random variables [CITATION_1] . Consequently, a MR random variable Z is such that P (Z > z) decays like O(e −z ) when the level z increases, and not like the Gaussian tail decay O(e −z 2 ). As described below (see Theorem 1), this has a clear impact on the sum of m independently and identically distributed (i.i.d.) MR random variables; this sum, seen as a random variable, has a tail that also decays exponentially when the level increases beyond a value only depending on the MR characteristics.",
